    "summary": "While my research projects are diverse in their empirical focus, they share a conceptual approach that explores three key themes: gender, violence, and protection. Since completing my PhD in 2020 I have developed 3 research projects that I outline below. These projects are all in early scoping phases, and my plan is to develop several individual and collaborative research grant proposals in 2022.\n\nProject Title: Gender and Disaster Response in Europe 2022-2023 \nRationale and Key Aims: Despite existing EU agendas to address gender based violence (GBV) and climate change little attention has been paid to the relationship between natural disasters and GBV. \n\nProject Title: Civil Society Influence and the Politics of Protection 2023-2026\nRationale and Key Aims: The study will examine how the international community interacts with civil society organizations (CSOs) in understanding when and how to respond to violence against civilians. The theoretical and empirical aims of this project can therefore be read as a continuation of my doctoral research. \n\nProject Title: Technologies of Deterrence: AI and Protection 2023-2027\nRationale and Key Aims: In a recent article Programming the Machine: Gender, Race, Sexuality, AI, and the construction of credibility and deceit at the border, my colleague Dr Clapton (UNSW, Australia) and I explored the EU\u2019s use of AI technologies as part of border and migration management practices. In this article we engaged with 3 sets of literature 1) risk and security 2) AI and ethics, and 3) race, gender, and (in)security. We are currently working to develop a proposal that will investigate how the EU and Australia use AI technologies in the areas of migration, refugee protection, and border control management. \n\nPrior to my PhD work I was employed at UNHCR\u2019s Global Learning Centre as a research and training officer. During this time I have developed particular expertise on the design and delivery of training for government counterparts and humanitarian workers on refugee law, the legal framework relating to internally displaced persons and sexual and gender-based violence.  This involves combining knowledge of the relevant areas of refugee law and developments in this field with different learning methodologies to promote the use and implementation of the relevant bodies of international law.",
