                    "company": "UNSW",
                    "description": "My doctoral research examines the gendered logic(s) of protection. Owing a significant intellectual debt to feminist scholars of International Relations (IR) and International Law who have demonstrated the gendered conceptualisation and practice of civilian protection (inter alia Gardam and Charlesworth 2000; Gardam and Jarvis 2001; Carpenter 2006; Sjoberg and Peet 2011 and Kinsella 2011) my PhD dissertation concentrates on the role of gendered logics in the discursive construction of protection norms. In armed conflict, the protection of internally displaced persons (IDPs) and the protection of civilians from mass atrocity crimes pose two distinct, yet interrelated, challenges to humanitarian and protection actors. During the 1990s, the failure to protect civilians and IDPs in Somalia, Bosnia and Rwanda from ethnic cleansing, war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide prompted the development of a series of \u2018new\u2019 protection norms. To excavate the gendered logics of protection I analyse three normative frameworks i) The Responsibility to Protect (R2P); ii) frameworks designed to guide the protection of IDPs (the Guiding Principles and the Kampala Convention) and the Women, Peace and Security Agenda. \n\nI treat these normative frameworks as case studies in order to investigate the gendered logics in the discursive construction of protection norms.",
                    "title": "PhD Candidate",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
